<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
I'm surprised at how fast individuals in this thread are willing to disregard:<BR>1)international law (that we agree to)<BR>2)how we will actually GO ABOUT creating change after a war with Iraq<BR>3)in some instances "the facts" themselves<P>   Internationally, the US’s ‘war on terror’ has taken action to destroy terrorism and ensure international security.  However, practically all of these actions have violated international law as described in the UN charter.  <BR>   <BR>The attacks on September 11th left America looking for a target.  US officials proclaimed those responsible would be found.  They said that the ‘war on terror’ would be a lengthy battle.  What does this foreshadow?  It foreshadows American responses to 9/11 in the form of military action even when it is in opposition to international law and common sense.  This action took the shape in the form of the Afghanistan campaign.  What justified American attacks in Afghanistan?  According to the US it was acting in “self defense”, the actions of 9/11 meant that Afghanistan posed a threat to the US and it must be addressed through military assaults.  However, were the attacks by the US and Britain against Afghanistan justified in the eyes of international law?  All signs point to no.  <BR>   <BR>The outlining of “self-defense” as the only reason for unilateral military action against prolonged attacks on the state was established by the League of Nations after WWI and has been accepted ever since.  September 11th was an attack against the state, however, the attack stopped.  There was no continued threat by any specific nation toward the US that would justify unilateral military action against a sovereign state.  Without the continuation of hostilities after 9/11 and without justification of a significant threat the US acted contrary to article 2(4) and article 51 that states that “a country is not permitted to use military force for purposes of retaliation, vengeance, and punishment”.  The state is also bound to show that the action is necessary to protect its citizens or territory and that the threat is so imminent and <BR>over-whelming as to leave no other choice.  Regardless of the Security Council offering TWO resolutions condemning the attacks of September 11th and offering LEGAL measures to combat terrorism and it’s financing (none of which authorize military action) the US and Britain entered Afghanistan and bombed it’s infrastructure.  In the case of Afghanistan other options were available and yet they were ignored.<BR>   <BR>The next campaign for the ‘war on terror’ to take on is that of Iraq.  The UN Charter in article 2(4) states succinctly, “All members shall refrain in their international relations from the threat of or use of force against the territorial integrity or political independence of any state, or in any manner inconsistent with the purposes of the United Nations.”  The  Bush administration claims that there are legitimate reasons in this case to invade Iraq and that they are supported by international law, however this is simply not the case.  In reality, he means to invade Iraq as ‘pre-emptive deterrence of a potential threat that isn’t supported by the current definition of self defense.  His administration has outlined 3 basic arguments for the need for military intervention as self-defense.  [the three reasons outlined here] That he (Saddam) is seeking nuclear weapons, that it has a history of using force in the region and it has shown a willingness to support terrorism.  In order for these claims to be legitimate in the eyes of international law the Bush administration must first show that the threat is imminent and over-whelming and no other options are available.  Simply put, the current arguments posed by the US are not sufficient to support this claim.  First, there is no connection between Iraq and the individuals that performed the actions of 9/11 (most of these individuals were Saudis).  As a matter of fact technology is being applied to internet searches to simply connect the words “al Qaeda” to “Saddam Hussein” and they still have found nothing.  Second, Saddam has not shown any indication of possessing nuclear weapons as well as other weapons of mass destruction.  Scott Ritter, a UN weapons inspector proclaimed that “'By 1998, the chemical weapons infrastructure had been completely dismantled or destroyed by UNSCOM or by Iraq in compliance with our mandate. The biological weapons programme was gone, all the major facilities eliminated. The nuclear weapons programme was completely eliminated. THe long-range ballistic missile programme was completely eliminated. If I had to quantify Iraq's threat, I would say [it is] zero.'”  Attempts by the UN to proceed with Iraq through inspections have garnered little support by Bush and his administration bent upon war rather than evidence of an actual threat.  This allows Bush to acquire support for a preemptive attack based on the notion of self-defense.  In other words “we don’t need evidence to prove that he will attack us, just the possibility”.  Henry Kissinger described pre-emptive attacks as “counter to modern international law, which sanctions the use of force in self-defense only against ACTUAL not POTENTIAL threats”.  In the end, unless he actually uses weapons of mass destructive, nukes or biological weaponry on us or shows a CLEAR and imminent possibility of doing so, then the US has not met it’s burden of proof.  Saddam has shown little indication in the past 10 years that he is willing to use force against the United States or other such powers.  He has shown little more than a desire to preserve his own life and regime and logically one would envision the usage of weapons of mass destruction or chemical agents against his neighbors or the US as being the signing of his own death warrant.  <BR>   <BR>People seem to forget the importance of International Law in maintaining a world of peace.  The UN and international laws were based upon events in history that showed how individuals and nations could use their power to destroy and dominate other people and nations.  Without international laws supported and respected by all it’s members, countries would be allowed to carry out actions based on their own self interest(and in this case it ISN'T in our self interest at all -- in fact it will work to our detriment) at the risk of international stability and the rights of people of the world.  This is exactly what is happening now with US unilateral military action under the guise of the ‘self-defense’ and US/international security.  Amnesty International, in a recent publication, describes a domino effect of rights violations that are occurring around the world under the auspices of the ‘war on terror’.  They outline security measures in 50 countries such as torture, indefinite detainment without charges, infringement of rights on free speech that makes them wonder if the ‘war on terror’ is becoming a ‘global dirty war’ in which rights are outweighed by national security.<P>There is no legal justification for a war with Iraq.  There is no connection of terrorists to Saddam and his regime that we currently possess.<P>Second, what happens once we DO overthrow Saddam's regime?  What are the specs of Iraq and the Middle East as it stands?<P>Well, first, Middle Easterners and Iraqis don't hate Americans.  Historically, we've been VERY friendly.. our first interactions with the people were pleasant and mutually beneficial.  Today, the disdain for Americans comes in the form of what Chalmers Johnson calls "Blowback" (the result of our actions abroad).  No one thinks out the reactions of the people to a military attack against international law and common sense in that region and how it will just create more terrorists.<P>Ok, let's say we do find a "justification" for war with Iraq.  What will be the costs of the endeavor before and after the situation.<P>Let's take a look at the region for a moment.<P>You currently have a a youth bulge where 2/3 the people are under the age of 30, 1/2 are under the age of 20 and there is a 2% population increase every year.  These individuals are being more and more educated every year.  While this is occuring living standards are going down...there is RAPID urbanization (cities population increasing 2X faster than other areas in the region) and a failure of the current government (under their own acts as well as under the acts -IE sanctions- of other nations which are not allowing the nation to grow).  There is a rapidly growing labor force in which is growing 8X faster than Europe and 4X faster than the US and yet there are not enough jobs for these people because of the current state of the region (this is basic economics folks.. the supply is greater than the demand so what happens?  Discontent.)  These individuals have a greater access to the internet and outside communication.  The current governments cannot support the countries (and a war with Iraq would stifle the country even further) so they turn to fundamentalist religious groups that can provide things for them.  If we destablalize the region and show these people that we are asserting force against a sovereign Arab nation it will do nothing but create more terrorists.<P>So we want to go to war here to create "peace" and help alleviate the problem.  I have a few questions...  Let's uncover the "fog of war" so many conservatives and military personnel LOVE to hide under...  What will be the costs in lives of those in the initial conflict?  Most reports indicate that battles will retreat to major cities where death tolls will significantly rise.  Where will the money come from to support another (as my professor so brilliantly calls) "drive by nation building".  According to US military/economists it will cost 50-80 BILLION dollars to do so.  NOT TO MENTION the fact that we are "developing" and "aiding" 4 other countries as it is.  Where is the money going to come from?<P>What about oil shock?  Will Americans put up with oil prices EXPLODING after a war with Iraq is initiated?<P>Who will take over in this region after Saddam is removed?  Wonder why no alternate groups step up to oppose Saddam?  BECAUSE THEY'LL DIE.  There is NO ONE to take over for Saddam as a new political party.  It will have to be a US military gov until a party steps up..but will he be a Kurd (more than likely not as Turkey will be annhilating them)..who will it be?<P>Will our nation building be effective?  What will we REALLY invest in this region?  (See Afghanistan fiasco).<P>Ok, let's get real people.  Lift the fog of war.  What does a war with Iraq mean in the LONG TERM?  We're attacking Iraq because it's easier to attack a STATE than collective terrorists cells.  That's why.  It's a bad idea.  There is no end game.  We will make more terrorists.  It will cost too much and we are not willing to invest.<P>P.S. The media IS NOT LIBERAL.<P><BR>I hope my ideas are logical and coherant.  I didn't have much time to prepare this little oration..in the future I will be sure to post when I have more free time to do so.
</FONT>
