Hello, you all dont know me but I have been a lurker here for some time, mainly for the entertainment value.  But this has got to be the one thing that made me decide to register and actually post something.<P>I dont know if this was addressed or not, there has been so much information posted and debated, but someone mentioned that Bush cannot declare war without the approval of Congress, which as far as I know is not true.  Bush can declare war for up to 30 days without approval if im not mistaken.<P>Also, the main reason that I belive the US is looking into war with Iraq is because of possible future threats to the US and its allies.  Why wait for anyone, including Saddam, to build up weapons that can be deployed to locations maximizing non-military personnel deaths? WOMD are designed to kill as many innocent non-combatants as possible, not destroy military targets.  Most nations use them as active deterrents, the same reason we have them and maintain a standing army/navy/marine corps/air force/coast gaurd.<P>Nobody (and I know I am using a strong/loaded word) will use nuclear weapons because of the fact that nobody can rule a planet with no life and only fallout.  Ever see wargames (the movie with Matthew Broderick)?  However, biological and chemical weapons can kill large amounts of soldiers and civillians, without much damage to the territory someone is trying to take over.  Any steps to prevent this should be taken.<P>When I graduate (not too far off now), I will be comissioned in the United States Navy as a Surface Warfare Officer, and then either off to Dive School or if I am really massochistic/lucky, BUD/S (SEAL) school. I will not be in the front line of fighting, but there is a large chance of my life being in more danger than 90% of Americans.  <P>My choice to join the military is because I want to take an active role in the defense and future of my country, and while from my writings so far, I may seem like a militaristic/crazy conservative, I really am not, trust me, please.  The unnecessary loss of life should not be condoned, or allowed by any person/nation/whatever.  For this reason the prevention of buildup of NBC weapons should not be allowed. Thus, action should be taken against nations that do so.  The US may be in posession of nuclear weapons, but to my knowledge (and I could be wrong), we do not posess any form of biological/chemical weapons.  Again, I could be wrong.  If we do have them, I seriously doubt we would ever use them. But I hope that the US has stopped the buildup of NBC weapons in our country, so that we are not the largest hippocites in the world.  <P>Is war the answer? I have no idea. Unfortunately most likely no one on this board will have any input as to wether or not war will occur, because from what I have read there are some highly intelligent people here.<P>Now for the part where I piss almost everyone off. <P>How can you say you are against war? If a citizen fails to support a war that their nation is involved in, then by all means leave.  There are plenty of other countries on the planet.  Please stop enjoying the protection that the US military provides you. But to truly be a person who follows your own principals, go live in a nation with no form of military.  See what life is like there.  Then realized how privildged you are to live in a nation that got to be this way because of land we fought and killed for, and then fought and killed for to defend.  You may not agree with why the war is being fought, but if you really care, run for office and change things on the inside. You can bitch all you want, but if you actually take action, I might not agree with you, but I will respect you for taking an active role with your beliefs.  Every nation in the world was founded by war, territories stolen from other people.  And now the nations that fared the best in those wars are on top of the global political structure.  <P>There are some nations that have flourished despite failures in battle.  Japan comes to mind.  But how much pull does Japan have outside of the global economy?  Do we put Japans opinions at the top of our list when considering taking military action against other countries? In this world, might makes right, and unfortunately there is not much we can do to change it. We have to play the hand we are dealt, and make the most out of this life.  <P>I know my post is long/opinionated, but this is how I feel on the matter.  Thank you for reading it all and any kind of criticism, agreement, whatever is more than welcome. Thats what debates are for.<P>--------------------<P>Rengak 46 Monk, Drinal<BR>Yeah, im uber (thats what i tell myself at least)
