Rengak, the founding fathers of America would be stunned that an American would take the approach that if you're against the policies of the current government you should "by all means leave." America is not the country that it is because our citizens bend over to the whim of whoever is in charge, it is the country it is because we celebrate dissent from the views of the masses. We celebrate criticism and debate. You certainly have more faith in the current government than I ever will but I think that it is misplaced simply because power corrupts. Our leaders are no more invulnerable to corruption than Saddam Hussein is, what prevents them from that extreme of corruption is criticism, dissent, open checks, and balances (all of which are fading.) Frankly I am more terrified of America as a country if the masses and government succumbed to any demand from the Executive branch than I would of Al Qaeda launching more assaults upon the US. Having an overwhelming population of people frightened enough to give in to any debate the executive branch presents with out reasoning or logic behind it other than what they heard on television is a bigger  problem than someone looking at the evidence at hand and saying this war is not justified or necessary.<P>Take this scenario for example - since the argued points for going to war mostly come from Conservative Republicans I've taken a tactic to debating them on the issue of blind faith on the President. Back track to the Clinton and Lewinsky affair - Hypothetical situation : Clinton decides to wage a war against Iraq to cover up this mess and distract the populace from his personal life. To justify it in a way that does not look like he's doing it to just cover himself up he claims Iraq is building weapons of mass destruction and is a active threat against the US. So he goes to war against Saddam. The irony is the liberals I've talked to would have supported this, the conservatives I've talked to were absolutely against it. My point is there have been members of the Bush Administration who've recognized and stated though not the primary reason Iraq will serve the interests of the Republicans and distract domestic issues. What if that was his only reason? Or a future President's reason for going to war to benefit himself? Go to war for the benefits of individuals seeking power and votes Those wars would not be justified, therefore a lack of dissent would be disastrous. Criticism, dissent, and debate are essential even critical to America's place as a super power. I am truly amazed anyone, liberal or conservative who stands by the values of America would be against debate. (I'm starting to come to the conclusion I'm a constitutionalist since neither liberal/conservative appeal to me with all the politics between them.)<P>I didn't come to my views of being against that war because I'm an uneducated idiot, I'm willing to put down 200 dollars I've studied as many angles as possible more extensively than most people here who are not privy to special information like some of the military folk may be. Education provides different insight, different ways to make judgements, and most importantly different perspectives. Most of the people I talked to outside of the voting building in my neighborhood were for the war based on reasons that had absolutely no merits or truth. In fact I did not talk to one person (These are your average Joe Americans) who had a legitimate reason for going to war. If the Average Joe's on the street would argue their support for war even 1/4th as well as a few of you in favor here I'd be much more confident in trusting them. But they don't. How could you say dissent is not important and in fact should be done away with when your average Americans are blindly trusting the media and administration with out questioning?<P>None of the people in favor of the war have answered my question or seemed to read my points other than Irontaail... Tell me once again why weapon inspections with the agreed merits of War if Iraq fails to comply won't work? The evidence is overwhelmingly in support that there is an absolute minimum 1 year before anything gets in to motion. More likely if by chance these weapons are being developed still leaning towards the realistic view  2 - 3 years. We are in no immediate threat from Iraq at this time. As the CIA director stated we are not a target at this time unless we provoke him.<P>The world and the US is at least smarter through experience in dealing with Iraq - I am not against war in that I realize there are times when it is necessary, and I stand by the claim that war is not necessary at this point on a hunch. As I posted earlier, America is pissed, the UN is pissed, even the countries against going to war want inspections in Iraq to resolve this issue. Put inspectors in Iraq with unrestricted access : resistance to specific spots or failure to comply all together will imply that nuclear weapons are being developed and thus justifying the war still years before the nuclear program in Iraq is likely to be ready. With that failure you will gain international support and the backing of the UN in removing Iraq, rebuilding it afterwards and staying in place to ensure stability. This is what is being debated now, and despite Bush's comments through the US media that the UN will be rendered irrelevant, our representatives in the UN have been debating and working out conditions that IMPLY all along that Bush wanted inspections with the fall back of war for failure. Had the media and Bush said this all along how many Americans do you think would blindly support going to war with out knowing why? The media along with Bush have shaped Americans in to a war mongering nation eager to "defend" itself on a hunch and what if questions years before the threat arises. That is aggression, not defense.<P>You must seek a balanced decision, you must debate these points, you must look at all angles and even if you're fully in support of the war you must dissent to find out if the views of your leaders are genuine. America has these freedoms and rights because of dissent, not blind patriotism. I value the views of educated dissent more than patriotism in that one must use logic and reasoning to come to its conclussion while the other will support regardless of the issues at hand (Unless it's educated patriotism, in which case I find it on a mutual level to educated dissent.)
