<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Apparently (and this is my fault)what I was thinking in my head and what I typed did not come out as clear as I hoped.<P>First, I said that is war the answer? I do not know.  But any steps than can be taken to prevent buildup and eventual use of NBC weapons should be taken.  If inspections do take place and in doing so, prevent the Iraq from obtaining these weapons, then many lives would be saved and the world would be a safer place.  If however, America has definite proof of Iraq's weapons and intent to use, then force of arms is the only way to go.  <P>I should have put a few extra sentences with my, "by all means leave" statement. Inactivity is one thing that really bothers me. People who complain about how the government is being run, yet take no action to change it. If all someone does is complain about US involvement, yet takes no steps to change the situation, then by all means leave. I do realize that the country was founded on dissent and civil disobedience. Yet show me a war that at the start of the conflict a strong majority of Americans were not in favor of. In Vietnam, most Americans were very supportive of US involvement in helping an underdog nation resist the terror of communism (I say 'terror of communism' with a slight hint of sarcasm   <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> ) But due to an enormous amount of increased media coverage, popular opinion swinged the other way.  Should we have gotten involved in Vietnam? The debate is still going on to this day. I believe we should have, not because of the bs reason of moral high ground, but because of the fact that I believe that people with power/riches/authority/strength/whatever should help those less fortunate.  Did America go about it the right way? I don't think so. Intentions were good, implementation was bad. Which is another reason why I don't know wether or not war with Iraq would be beneficial.<P>What I do know is that steps need to be taken against people who show the desire to use NBC weapons. As I said before, these weapons greatest potential is to wipe out civilian life. Not destroy bunkers, air defense, or other military targets, but your neighbors. I also do not believe in blind faith in the government, but I came across that way. For giving you that impression I am terribly sorry. I know that it seems like I am reversing my position, but please read on. In times of war the government needs the support of the citizens, wether it is by actual support of taking steps to prove beyond a shadow of a doubt that Americas involvement is wrong for many reasons. What those reasons are I leave up to you. But if it does come to war and you convince me that we should not be there, then we definetly should not be there. <P>People die every day. The purpose of wars is to keep as many of your citizens alive as you can. The reason the US has gotten involved in peacekeeping actions lately is because of the threat to more American lives if the enemies of America are allowed to grow too powerful.  Were the top nation in the world, and the only way to keep that spot is by keeping our enemies weaker than we are. This policy applies to everyones everyday lives. Businesses sqaush their competitors to keep the money rolling in. Gangs kill rivals to keep their money rolling in. And in EQ some people KS/crash zones/whatever to keep other people from gaining the uber stuff (im not saying that Triton does it, but it does happen).<P>To keep America stong and the citizens safe, action needs to be taken. Once again, I do not know if war is the answer, but if it comes to war I have faith that it will be because peace has failed. <P>I know that I came off as very hotheaded, assholish, whatever. But at times I can get that way. I just get angry whenever I see people saying that we should never engage in armed conflict. I have faith in the elected officials (maybe too much)that they would never start a full on war only to keep themselves in power. That is the reason that I hate midterm elections.  Any intitution that has policies in place to keep its members in power has alot of problems. I know that the American government has these, but unfortunately it is the best system that man can get to work.<P><BR>Whew, I finally stopped typing and just read what I wrote. Ok, in summary <BR>1) Take an active role in the issues you care about. If you don't, then stay quiet, you get out of government what you put into it.<BR>2) Try to resolve things peacefully, if that doesn't work, and physically removing the WOMD from Iraq is the only way to protect America and its allies, then that is what we have to do. <BR>3) It didn't mention this earlier, but I think I need to say it.  I hate false patriotism. Before 9/11 people had about a 27%(arbitrary number) level of patriotism. All of a sudden America finally gets a taste of what the middle east/balkans/africa has and its 100% USA. Don't get me wrong, it was a terrible thing, and we should be supportive and come together, but all the profiting off the event sickens me. I can see the same thing starting to happen now, and I am starting to get worried. <BR>4) Hopefully the implementation of the Bush administrations policies will be better than what has happened in the past. Unfortunately, only time will tell.<BR>5) The fist soap was made from the ashes of heroes - Tyler Durden<P>--------------------<P>Rengak 46 Monk, Drinal<BR>Yeah, im uber (thats what i tell myself at least)
